\end{array}\right)=-i\gamma^{2}\gamma^{0}
\]

\end_inset

which is easy to verify.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So let us use this term finally to define a different mass term.
 I write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{2}\mathcal{L}_{\text{Majorana Mass}} & \sim & m\psi^{T}C\psi\\
 & = & -im\left(\Psi_{L}^{T}+\Psi_{R}^{T}\right)\gamma^{2}\gamma^{0}\left(\Psi_{L}+\Psi_{R}\right)\\
 & = & -im\left(\Psi_{L}^{T}\gamma^{2}\gamma^{0}\Psi_{L}+\Psi_{R}^{T}\gamma^{2}\gamma^{0}\Psi_{R}\right)\\
 & = & m\left(\Psi_{L}^{T}C\Psi_{L}+\Psi_{R}^{T}C\Psi_{R}\right)
\end{alignedat}
\]

\end_inset

so here I have arrived at a mass term which does 
\emph on
mix 
\emph default
the left and right spinors! I'd point out that this object ofcourse is not
 guaranteed to be real.
 To ensure that, we must add its hermitian conjugate (
\begin_inset Formula $-m\psi^{\dagger}C\psi^{*}$
\end_inset

).
 To conclude this subsection, I'd mention that 
\end_layout

